\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Intelligent design propentisists love the word complexity. They believe that it is a hallmark of design, and thus, evidence for a designer. I\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92ve always thought this position to be a bit odd, because in my experience, simplicity and elegance are the hallmarks of good design, not complexity. Complexity is usually (not always) a sign that the designer in question was figuring things out as they went along.  Early iterations of a product may be extremely complex, while later iterations simplify, condense, and eliminate waste. An example I\u8217\'92d point to is the development of the SpaceX [Raptor engine](}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.reddit.com/media?url=https%3A%2F%2Fpreview.redd.it%2Fuljsgjiee2vd1.png%3Fwidth%3D2048%26format%3Dpjpg%26auto%3Dwebp%26s%3Da1b766d5c2a27094eb0250f8b20e1ebbb98f1f9c"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24 https://www.reddit.com/media?url=https%3A%2F%2Fpreview.redd.it%2Fuljsgjiee2vd1.png%3Fwidth%3D2048%26format%3Dpjpg%26auto%3Dwebp%26s%3Da1b766d5c2a27094eb0250f8b20e1ebbb98f1f9c}}{). But this preference for simplicity over complexity can be found in just about every field of human activity, from graphic design, right on down theoretical physics. The basic principle here is that, whenever a simpler solution results in the same (or better) effect as a complex solution, the simpler solution is preferred.}
\par\plain 
