\par\plain {\tab B\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 Coding Region\line \line The crux of the matter is step two: duplicate. The reduncancy of duplication incurs a fitness cost for no immediate gain. Because of this, no one expected that duplicate genes would stay around long enough within a population to contribute much in the way of complexity as the duplications would be purged by natural selection. This turns out to be true, but only in large populations as you might see in prokaryotic life. For smaller populations, selection will be less effective because the randomizing potential of genetic drift is sufficiently strong. In other words, random chance events which have no real bearing on fitness (e.g. a random cow in a field cows getting struck by lightning) have a strong effect on allele frequency, overriding the effect of selection. It has been shown that these gene duplications can have a small enough effect on fitness that realistically small population sizes can allow these mutations to persist and contribute to the increasing complexity of the genome, and thus, the organism. This interplay between drift and selection is referred to as the [drift-barrier hypothesis](}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.pnas.org/doi/10.1073/pnas.1216223109"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24 https://www.pnas.org/doi/10.1073/pnas.1216223109}}{). There is decent (supporting)[}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://elifesciences.org/reviewed-preprints/93629"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24 https://elifesciences.org/reviewed-preprints/93629}}{] evidence.}
